         <h1>Pierre Restany, 72, Formulator Of 'New Realism' School in Art </h1>
           <div class="row">
               <div class="col-md-10">
 					<p class="text-left">
<blue>1</blue>Pierre Restany , an influential French art critic and curator , died in Paris on May 29 . <br><blue>2</blue>He was 72 and lived in Paris and Milan . <br><blue>3</blue>The cause was heart failure , said Isabella Di Nunno , assistant to the editor of Domus magazine . <br><blue>4</blue>Mr. Restany was best known as one of the founders and a tireless promoter of the European movement of the 1960 's called the New Realism . <br><blue>5</blue>Emphasizing found materials rather than representational imagery or formalist abstraction , the New Realism included artists like Yves Klein , who covered all kinds of objects with his signature '' International Klein Blue '' paint ; Arman , who created accumulations of junk or store-bought objects ; Christo , who wrapped found objects in fabric and rope ; Jean Tinguely , who constructed absurd , self-destroying machines ; and Daniel Spoerri , who made sculpture by gluing the remains of meals to dining tables . <br><blue>6</blue>As a young art critic in 1955 , Mr. Restany met Klein , and this encounter inspired his theory of an art that would be closer to real-life experience than Pop Art or Modernist abstraction . <br><blue>7</blue>The New Realism was inaugurated in 1960 with exhibitions at Mr. Restany 's own Gallery J. in Paris and with manifestoes by Mr. Restany announcing the advent of a new , socially relevant art in the Dada tradition . <br><blue>8</blue>Pierre Restany was born in Am√©lie-les-Bains , France , on June 24 , 1930 . <br><blue>9</blue>He grew up in Morocco and attended universities in France , Italy and Ireland . <br><blue>10</blue>In 1963 , he began writing regularly for Domus , the Italian magazine of art and architecture . <br><blue>11</blue>In 1984 , he helped found the Domus Academy in Milan , a post-graduate research institute for fashion and design . <br><blue>12</blue>Beginning in 1985 , he edited the Milan-based magazine D'Ars . <br><blue>13</blue>Mr. Restany wrote many articles for European art magazines and many books , including the first monograph on Klein . <br><blue>14</blue>During the last two decades he wrote extensively about issues relating to art and urban planning . <br><blue>15</blue>He frequently participated in organizing large international exhibitions , including the Olympic Sculpture Park in Seoul in the late 1980 's and , more recently , the 1999 Venice Biennale , as well as shows in Shanghai and Havana ( both in 2000 ) and in Istanbul ( 2001 ) . <br><blue>16</blue>He served as president of the Palais de Tokyo contemporary art center in Paris since January 2002 . <br><blue>17</blue>Mr. Restany , who married four times , is survived by his wife , Josianne de Koch Restany . <br><hr><br><blue>1(3)</blue>: <m_str>the New Realism</m_str> (5_12) 	<m_str>The New Realism</m_str> (7_1) 	<m_str>the New Realism</m_str> (4_24) 	<br><blue>2(2)</blue>: <m_str>Klein</m_str> (13_19) 	<m_str>Klein</m_str> (6_12) 	<br><blue>3(2)</blue>: <m_str>Milan</m_str> (11_11) 	<m_str>Milan</m_str> (2_9) 	<br><blue>4(2)</blue>: <m_str>Domus , the Italian magazine of art and architecture</m_str> (10_9) 	<m_str>the Domus Academy in Milan , a post-graduate research institute for fashion and design</m_str> (11_7) 	<br><blue>5(3)</blue>: <m_str>Paris</m_str> (7_18) 	<m_str>Paris</m_str> (16_14) 	<m_str>Paris</m_str> (1_14) 	<br><blue>6(18)</blue>: <m_str>He</m_str> (15_1) 	<m_str>He</m_str> (2_1) 	<m_str>Mr. Restany 's</m_str> (7_11) 	<m_str>Mr. Restany , who married four times</m_str> (17_1) 	<m_str>Mr. Restany</m_str> (4_1) 	<m_str>Pierre Restany</m_str> (8_1) 	<m_str>his</m_str> (17_12) 	<m_str>he</m_str> (10_4) 	<m_str>Mr. Restany announcing the advent of a new , socially relevant art in the Dada tradition</m_str> (7_23) 	<m_str>Mr. Restany</m_str> (6_9) 	<m_str>his</m_str> (5_28) 	<m_str>he</m_str> (12_5) 	<m_str>He</m_str> (16_1) 	<m_str>he</m_str> (14_6) 	<m_str>his</m_str> (6_18) 	<m_str>He</m_str> (9_1) 	<m_str>he</m_str> (11_4) 	<m_str>Mr. Restany</m_str> (13_